INSITRO.name: Insitro
INSITRO.tagline: Accelerating drug discovery by combining machine learning with biology at scale
INSITRO.overview: Insitro is an AI-first drug discovery company founded in 2018 by Daphne Koller, Stanford professor and Coursera co-founder. The company uses machine learning to redefine disease biology and accelerate drug development. Insitro raised $643M+ at $2.5B valuation from investors including T. Rowe Price, ARCH Ventures, Andreessen Horowitz, and Jeff Bezos. Major pharma partnerships include Gilead (metabolic diseases) and Bristol Myers Squibb (NASH, ALS). CEO Koller was a 2004 MacArthur 'genius' grant recipient.

funding_rounds.investors_html: a16z, ARCH, GV, Foresite, Third Rock

IDME.name: ID.me
IDME.tagline: Digital identity verification platform securing access to government services and benefits
IDME.overview: ID.me is a leading digital identity verification platform that simplifies how individuals securely prove their identity online. Founded in 2010 by Blake Hall, a decorated Army Ranger, the company has evolved from serving military communities to becoming the trusted identity partner for government agencies, healthcare organizations, and enterprises. ID.me enables users to verify their identity once and seamlessly access services across multiple platforms without repeated verification. As of 2025, the platform serves over 152 million users, including 20 federal agencies, 45 state government agencies, and more than 70 healthcare organizations, preventing billions in fraud while ensuring secure access to critical services.

highlights.text: Raised $340M in Series E funding at $2B+ valuation led by Ribbit Capital.
Expanded to 20 federal agencies and 45 state government agencies.
Served 152+ million users with government identity verification.
Prevented $270B+ in identity fraud across government programs.
Enhanced IRS integration with optional facial recognition alternatives.

investors.name: Federal Government Portal: Access to IRS, SSA, VA, and other federal services.
